Better about yourself. My inclusivity isn’t about you. It’s about me wanting to feel like I’m actually a part of a family.

These issues will never be mine and my disability’s fault. Because I’ve fought tooth and nail to accept who I am and be comfortable here and being told at the dinner table that I need to be fixed, that my disability doesn’t define me, ERASES all that hard work for you to feel
RT @adrianjbailey: Sign language gloves are a really expensive way to say you’re just not that interested in learning sign languages
This kind of cycle ends when you include us. When you ask us what can be done to make the holidays easier and more joyful. More inclusive. Don’t make assumptions, don’t pretend. Ask.

And sitting in the living room and crying my eyes out. And still no one even noticed I wasn’t there or came to check on me. I remember thinking maybe I can just watch the TV, only for there not to be captions and still not fully getting to enjoy it and getting more frustrated.

—it’s just that. Sitting at your table. I’m not getting the full experience of holiday joy and that’s not my or my disability’s fault. You just refuse to change. I remember being 9 and leaving my family in the kitchen because I had all these feelings and no way to explain it

I don’t want to be talked about at the dinner table or just watch you laugh and pretend like I understand what’s being said. I want to know what’s being said and when you don’t even bother meeting me in the middle, that’s not inclusive. If I am just sitting at your table—

If you’re related to a Deaf person or you’re dating somebody deaf, check on us especially during the holidays. We are so exhausted. 
I’ve never fully been included in a holiday. My family would disagree but that’s because they don’t understand what it means to include me

And then I’m expected to blame myself because in past holidays my own family made excuses not to learn even a bit of sign by saying a cochlear implant would fix me and since I won’t participate in the expensive as fuck surgery that’s hardly successful, it must be my fault.

Every holiday I am reminded why I’m afraid to take up space. Because I’m not included. I’m hardly a guest, I’m a ghost made to sit in the corner and watch people enjoy their conversations when I get no part of the joy.

Fully welcome. I never told him about my feelings from that day. I just remember sitting next to him watching him smile and talk and having no idea what was being said and wanting to cry. At both mine and his family’s. I was so tired by the end of the day.

There was talking and laughter, I’m sure they were asking how we met, where he worked, nobody stopped and checked on me. I even had a dry erase board and a marker. They used it only a handful of times and were not consistent about keeping me included. I felt like I wasn’t

I remember one thanksgiving, my hearing aid was broken. I was dating a new guy at the time. So I celebrated thanksgiving with him and his family and also he with my family. Both family thanksgiving lunch and dinner, I had no idea what was being said. The entire time.

Bounce back and forth too quickly for us to even lipread. When we do lipread, it gets so exhausting so fast. This is also a time where our disability gets brought up in conversation and we are made to answer uncomfortable and invasive questions just because they are family

My family doesn’t get why I don’t come around for the holidays yet every single holiday I’ve had with them I experience something in the Deaf community if you’re unfamiliar we call Dinner Table Syndrome, where we get completely left out of conversations because people 1/?
